-- Stocks in South Africa Gain for Second Day: Anglo Platinum, Billiton Move
-- B y   A n a   M o n t e i r o
-- 2010-10-29T15:52:43Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-29/stocks-in-south-africa-fall-for-a-3rd-day-in-4-led-by-anglo-bhp-sasol.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  gained for a second day, adding 244.32, or 0.8
percent, to 30,430.90 by the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg. The
measure has advanced 3.3 percent this month, a second of
increases.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ), surged the most since Sept.
1, rallying 23 rand, or 3.4 percent, to 693 rand. The world’s
largest producer of the metal said entered talks that may have a
“material effect” on the company’s share price.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, rose for a second day, adding 68 cents, or 0.3 percent,
to 246.68 rand. Potash Corp. of Saskatchewan Inc. Chief
Executive Officer Bill Doyle urged patience for investors
expecting an alternative to BHP’s $40 billion bid, two months
after starting talks with potential suitors.  Avusa Ltd.  (AVU SJ), a South African media company, slumped
the most since July 29, dropping 1.56 rand, or 6.5 percent, to
22.50 rand. The company completed acquisition of Universal Print
Group Ltd. and Hirt & Carter Ltd. from UHC Communications Ltd.  Brait SA  (BAT SJ), a Luxembourg-based investment and
merchant bank, declined for the first time in five days,
slumping 60 cents, or 2.4 percent, to 24.20 rand. The company’s
operating environment continues to pose uncertainties,
especially given the global economic outlook, it said in a
stock-exchange filing today. Brait said first-half profit
climbed 50 percent to 116 million rand ($17 million).  Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ), the world’s largest producer of motor
fuels from coal, retreated 2.28 rand, or 0.7 percent, to 315.41
rand, paring its increase this month to 0.8 percent. Oil dropped
as much as 1.1 percent to $81.27 a barrel in London trading.  Vodacom Group Ltd.  (VOD SJ), the biggest provider of
mobile-phone services to South Africans, increased for a second
day, adding 46 cents, or 0.7 percent, to 67.30 rand. . The
company’s peak mobile termination fee will drop to 40 cents in
2013, South Africa’s telecommunications regulator said today.  “The agreed glide path gives us time to adjust our business
model in order to accommodate the significant further revenue
reduction that will result from the changes,” the company said
in an e-mailed statement today.  To contact the reporter on the story:
